body:
As someone new to Rust but who has had a fare amount of C++ experience, I think one thing that could be helpful for new Rust developers would be a small discussion about how references in Rust differ semantically than what is found in C++.  Since they both use the `&` operator, I incorrectly imposed my C++ expectations onto how the references work in Rust. I think a good place for this would be in the [references and borrowing section](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/references-and-borrowing.html).

An example to illustrate.

C++:

``` cpp
void swap(int &a, int &b) {
    int temp = a;
    a = b;
    b = temp;
    return;
}
```

Rust:

``` rust
fn swap(x: &mut i32, y: &mut i32) {
    let temp = *x;
    *x = *y;
    *y = temp;
}
```

I was initially confused by the need for the `*` operator in Rust to dereference a reference since C++ does this implicitly.  This was compounded by the fact that when you call methods on objects with `.`, a `*` isn't required, so I had seen many reference examples without `*`.  In the beginner's chat room a very friendly community member explained to me that `.` automatically dereferences when needed (which I was grateful for!).

I'm happy to submit a PR, but I'm not sure exactly the best way to word this (if this is even something others think would be helpful).  If I totally missed this in the docs already I'm happy to be pointed to it. :)
